docs.lead_paragraph: DEATH OF MRS. WEBSTER.--Mrs. CATHARINE WEBSTER, widow of the late Professor JOHN W: WEBSTER, of Harvard University, and halfsister to W. H. PRESCOTT, the historian, died, at her residence in Cambridge, on Monday. She had been sick but 36 hours, though her health has never been good since the fearful event which made her a Widow.

docs.lead_paragraph: MAJOR J. V. L. -OVERBAGH.-On Friday, Major J. V. L. OVERBAGH died at Saugerties, of an apoplectic fit. He had enjoyed uninterrupted health up to Thursday evening, when he attended a Lodge of Odd Fellows, and returned home apparently cheerful.

headline.main: RELIGIOUS INTELLIGENCE.; MISSIONARY OPERATIONS. American Board of Commissioners for Foreign Missions.

docs.lead_paragraph: The afternoon session commenced by singing a hymn. Several committees were then appointed. Rev. Mr. TREAT read a report on " The Preservation of the American Indians." The point to substantiate is, that a portion of the Indians can be preserved.

headline.main: ARRIVAL OF THE ILLINOIS.; $1,218,811 IN SPECIE. ISTHMUS NEWS.

docs.lead_paragraph: The steamship Illinois, Lieut. H. J. HARTSTRINE, U. S. N., commanding, left Aspinwall at 11 1/2 o'clock on the evening of the 1st inst., and arrived at Quarrantine at 91/2 o'clock on the forenoon of the 9th.

docs.lead_paragraph: ALDERMRN'S DOINGS--The Aldermen, becoming indignant at the bold stand of the Corporation Counsel in reference to the JONES' Wood Park case, last night adopted a resolution empowering the Mayor and Comptroller to employ other counsel to effect a stay of proceedings until application can be made to the next Legislature for the repeal of the Act.
